\title{Discriminant}
\author{alex-nelson}
\import{notation}
\date{2025-12-23}
\taxon{definition}

\p{Let #{x_{1}}, \dots, #{x_{n}} be a set of numbers. Their \define{Discriminant} is
##{D=\prod_{i<j}(x_{i}-x_{j})^{2}.}
The discriminant of a polynomial is the discriminant of its roots.}

\rmk{It's easy to see #{D} is invariant under transpositions, hence under all the elements of #{S_{n}}. Therefore #{D} is a function of #{s_{1}}, \dots, #{s_{n}}.}